2. Output redirection and error redirection results
Commands:
ls -l /etc/passwd /fake_directory > success.txt 2> error.txt
cat success.txt
cat error.txt
Output:
muskan_bhardwaj@LAPTOP-JR42J90G:~$ cat success.txt
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 1502 Jul  3 16:33 /etc/passwd
muskan_bhardwaj@LAPTOP-JR42J90G:~$ cat error.txt
ls: cannot access '/fake_directory': No such file or directory
Observation: The `>` operator effectively captured the standard output (FD 1) from the successful `/etc/passwd` query and saved it into `success.txt`. Meanwhile, the `2>` operator caught the standard error (FD 2) from the failed `/fake_directory` query and routed it into `error.txt`, keeping the streams isolated.

