4. Explanation of how Linux manages file I/O
In Linux, the core design principle is that almost everything is treated as a file, from standard text documents to hardware interfaces. To manage interactions with these files, the operating system assigns a unique integer called a File Descriptor (FD) to each open stream. Every process is automatically provided with FD 0 (Standard Input), FD 1 (Standard Output), and FD 2 (Standard Error). This numbering system makes it incredibly straightforward to pipe and redirect data or error logs across different files and applications.
